The slope and degree of adjustment that shows our set of species are quite surprising given the diversity of living forms used in this analysis. Our array of organism from the shortest single-strand RNA genome of \textit{Hepatitis D} virus (size $\sim 1.69e^{+03}$ bp) to the largest double-strand DNA genome of the short-tailed opossum \textit{Monodelphis domestica} (size $\sim 3.41e^{+09}$ bp), this, even including organisms among those with most peculiar genomes as can be:
\begin{itemize}
\item obligate endosymbionts bacteria with extreme reduction of genome size (\textit{Carsonella ruddii}, \textit{Buchnera aphidicola}, and \textit{Ureaplasma urealyticum}) \cite{Wernegreen2002}
\item parthenogenetic crustaceans with ubiquitous duplications of genes (\textit{Daphnia pulex})
\item archean organisms living in extreme environmental conditions (\textit{Sulfolobus islandicus}, \textit{Methanocaldococcus vulcanius}, \textit{Thermococcus sibiricus})
\item the first synthetic organism (\textit{Synthetic mycoplasma mycoides}) \cite{Gibson2010}
\end{itemize}

All of them fit the slope of the linear regression model.
