In order to better contrast deviations from maximum complexity we computed the complexity ratio (CR), and the deviation to the maximum ratio (Dmax = 1 - CR) for each species. According to \autoref{tab:genome}, only ten species showed Dmax $>$ 0.05. These are:
\begin{itemize}
\item six ancient or recent polyploid species; the most extreme case of genome reduction in bacteria
\item the explosive case of gene expansion in Daphnia\cite{Colbourne2011}
\item two unicellular eukaryotes that curiously correspond to the 2 genomes sequenced with higher proportion of A + T, \textit{Plasmodium} \cite{Gardner2002} (A + T content around 81\%) and \textit{Dictyostelium} \cite{Eichinger2003} (A + T content around 78\%)
\end{itemize}

The highest CR=1 was obtained for randomly generated sequences with uniform distribution of A C G T. To simulate events of polyploidization random sequences were duplicated up to 5 times (corresponding to a 10$\times$). The fall in CR reaching CR=0.25 for 10$\times$ could thus be compared to CR values of real polyploids placing maize genomes at the level of a perfect triploid and sorghum to the level of a perfect diploid.

Besides genomes and random sequences, results of the computation of CR of human texts were added to \fref{fig:gen_compl}{-B} (values used can be found in \autoref{tab:book_compl}).

